},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§25§ فَإِذا شكوا فِي مَوْلُود أَهَدَوْا لَهُ هَدِيَّةً ثُمَّ ضَرَبُوا بِالْقِدَاحِ, فَإِن خرج صَرِيح ألحقوه وَإِن خرج ملصق دَفَعُوهُ.",
 "English Sentence":"§60§ Whenever the lineage of a new-born was doubted, they would offer a sacrifice to it \"Hubal\" and then shuffle the arrows and throw them. §61§ If the arrows showed the word \"pure,\" the child would be declared legitimate and the tribe would accept him. §62§ If, however, the arrows showed the words \"consociated alien,\" the child would be declared illegitimate and the tribe would reject him."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§26§ وَقِدْحٌ عَلَى الْمَيِّتِ وَقِدْحٌ عَلَى النِّكَاحِ وَثَلاثَةٌ لَمْ تُفَسَّرْ لِي عَلَى مَا كَانَتْ.",
 "English Sentence":"§63§ The third arrow was for divination concerning the dead, while the fourth was for divination concerning marriage. §64§ The purpose of the three remaining arrows has not been explained."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§27§ فَإِذَا اخْتَصَمُوا فِي أمرٍ أَوْ أَرَادُوا سَفَرًا أَوْ عَمَلا أَتَوْهُ فَاسْتَقْسَمُوا بِالْقِدَاحِ عِنْدَهُ, فَمَا خَرَجَ عَمِلُوا بِهِ وَانْتَهَوْا إِلَيْهِ.",
 "English Sentence":"§65§ Whenever they disagreed concerning something, or purposed to embark upon a journey, or undertake some project, they would proceed to it \"Hubal\" and shuffle the divination arrows before it. §66§ Whatever result they obtained they would follow and do accordingly."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§28§ فَلَمَّا ظهر رَسُولُ اللَّهِ صَلَّى اللَّهُ عَلَيْهِ وَسَلَّمَ يَوْمَ فَتْحِ مَكَّةَ دَخَلَ الْمَسْجِدَ وَالأَصْنَامُ مَنْصُوبَةٌ حَوْلَ الْكَعْبَةِ فَجَعَلَ يَطْعَنُ بِسِيَةِ قَوْسِهِ فِي عُيُونِهَا وَوُجُوهِهَا وَيَقُولُ {جَاءَ الْحَقُّ وَزَهَقَ الْبَاطِلُ إِنَّ الْبَاطِل كَانَ زهوقاً} ثُمَّ أَمَرَ بِهَا فَكُفِئَتْ عَلَى وُجُوهِهَا, ثُمَّ أخرجت من الْمَسْجِد فَحُرِّقَتْ.",
 "English Sentence":"§67§ When, on the day he conquered Mecca, the Apostle of God appeared before the Ka’bah, he found the idols arrayed around it. §68§ Thereupon he started to pierce their eyes with the point of his arrow saying, \"Truth is come and falsehood is vanished. §69§ Verily, falsehood is a thing that vanisheth.\" §70§ He then ordered that they be knocked down, after which they were taken out and burned."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§29§ وَاسْتَهْتَرَتِ الْعَرَبُ فِي عِبَادَةِ الأَصْنَامِ\" فَمِنْهُمْ مَنِ اتَّخَذَ بَيْتًا, وَمِنْهُمْ مَنِ اتَّخَذَ صَنَمًا, وَمَنْ لَمْ يَقْدِرْ عَلَيْهِ وَلا عَلَى بِنَاءِ بيتٍ نَصَبَ حَجَرًا أَمَامَ الْحَرَمِ وَأَمَامَ غَيْرِهِ مِمَّا اسْتَحْسَنَ, ثُمَّ طَافَ بِهِ كطوافه بِالْبَيْتِ, وسموها الأنصاب.",
 "English Sentence":"§71§ The Arabs were passionately fond of worshipping idols. §72§ Some of them took unto themselves a temple around which they centered their worship, while others adopted an idol to which they offered their adoration. §73§ The person who was unable to build himself a temple or adopt an idol would erect a stone in front of the Sacred House or in front of any other temple which he might prefer, and then circumambulate it in the same manner in which he would circumambulate the Sacred House. §74§ The Arabs called these stones baetyls (ansab(."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§30§ فَأَقْبَلَ رَجُلٌ مِنْهُم بإبلٍ لَهُ لِيَقِفَهَا عَلَيْهِ يَتَبَرَّكُ بِذَلِكَ فِيهَا فَلَمَّا أَدْنَاهَا مِنْهُ نفرت مِنْهُ وَكَانَ يهراق عَلَيْهِ الدِّمَاء فَذَهَبَتْ فِي كُلِّ وجهٍ وَتَفَرَّقَتْ عَلَيْهِ, وَأَسِفَ فَتَنَاوَلَ حَجَرًا فَرَمَاهُ بِهِ وَقَالَ لَا بَارَكَ اللَّهُ فِيكَ إِلَهًا أَنَفَّرْتَ عَلَيَّ إِبِلِي.",
 "English Sentence":"§75§ Once upon a time a certain man \"belonging to one of these tribes\" came to it with his flock of camels in order to make them stand on it and thereby obtain its blessing. §76§ But as he led them near the rock they shied away from it because it was covered with blood, and they scattered in every direction. §77§ Thereupon the man became furious, and picked up a stone and threw it at the rock saying, \"Accursed god! §78§ Thou hast caused my camels to shy."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§31§ حَدَّثَنَا أَبُو عَلِيٍّ الْعَنَزِيُّ قَالَ حَدَّثَنَا عَلِيُّ بْنُ الصَّباح قَالَ أخبرنَا أَبُو الْمُنْذر هِشَام ابْن مُحَمَّدِ بْنِ السَّائِبِ الْكَلْبِيُّ قَالَ أَخْبَرَنِي أَبِي قَالَ أؤل مَا عُبِدَتِ الأَصْنَامُ أَنَّ آدَمَ عَلَيْهِ السَّلامُ لما مَاتَ, جعله بَنو شِيث بن آدم فِي مغارة فِي الْجَبَل الَّذِي أهبط عَلَيْهِ آدم بِأَرْضِ الْهِنْدِ.",
 "English Sentence":"§79§ I was told by abu-’Ali al-’Anazi on the authority of ‘Ali ibn-al-Sabbah that abu-al-Mundhir Hisham ibn-Muham- mad ibn-al-Sa’ih al-Kalbi related to him that his father once told him that what had given rise to the worship of idols was the following\" When Adam died the children of Seth (Shith), the son of Adam, buried him in a cave in the whereon Adam alighted (when he was sent) to the land of India."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§32§ وَيُقَالُ لِلْجَبَلِ نوذُ وَهُو أَخْصَبُ جبل فِي الأَرْض.",
 "English Sentence":"§80§ (The name of the mountain is Nawdh, and it is the most fertile mountain in all the world. §81§ Hence the saying, \"More fertile than Nawdh and more arid than Barahut."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§33§ وَيُقَال أمرع من نوذ وأجدب من بَرَهُوتَ وَبَرَهُوتُ وادٍ بِحَضْرَمَوْتَ بِقَرْيَةٍ يُقَالُ لَهَا تِنْعَةُ.",
 "English Sentence":"§81§ Hence the saying, \"More fertile than Nawdh and more arid than Barahut. §82§ Barahut is a valley in Hadra-mawt, in \"the Vicinity of\" a village called Tin’ah."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§34§ حَدَّثَنَا الْحَسَنُ بْنُ عليلٍ قَالَ حَدَّثَنَا عَلِيُّ بْنُ الصَّبَّاحِ قَالَ أَخْبَرَنَا أَبُو الْمُنْذِرِ قَالَ وَأَخْبَرَنِي أَبِي قَالَ\" كَانَ ود وسواع ويغرث وَيَعُوقُ وَنَسْرٌ قَوْمًا صَالِحِينَ مَاتُوا فِي شهرٍ.",
 "English Sentence":"§83§ I was told by al-Hasan ibn-’Ulayl on the authority of ‘Ali ibn-al-Sabbah that abu-al-Mundhir related on the authority of his father the following\" Wadd, Suwaf, Yaghuth, Ya’uq, and Nasr were righteous people who died within one month of one another, and their relatives were grief-stricken over them."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§35§ فَجَزِعَ عَلَيْهِمْ ذَوُو أَقَارِبِهِمْ.",
 "English Sentence":"§84§ Then One of the children of Cain addressed their relatives saying, \"O ye who are bereaved!"
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§36§ فَقَالَ رَجُلٌ مِنْ بَنِي قَابِيلَ \"يَا قَوْمُ هَلْ لَكُمْ أَنْ أعمل لكم خَمْسَةَ أَصْنَامٍ عَلَى صُوَرِهِمْ غَيْرَ أَنِّي لَا أَقْدِرُ أَنْ أَجْعَلَ فِيهَا أَرْوَاحًا؟\"",
 "English Sentence":"§85§ Shall I make unto you five statues after the image of your departed relatives’? §86§ I can readily, although I cannot impart life to them."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§37§ قَالُوا\" نَعَمْ!",
 "English Sentence":"§87§ Thereupon he carved unto them five statues after the image of \"their departed relatives\", and erected them \"over their graves."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§38§ فَنَحَتَ لَهُمْ خَمْسَةَ أَصْنَامٍ عَلَى صُوَرِهِمْ وَنَصَبَهَا لَهُم.",
 "English Sentence":"§87§ Thereupon he carved unto them five statues after the image of \"their departed relatives\", and erected them \"over their graves. §88§ Another century followed during which people venerated and respected those statues more than they did during the first century."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§39§ ثُمَّ جَاءَ قَرْنٌ آخَرُ فَعَظَّمُوهُمْ أَشَدَّ مِنْ تَعْظِيمِ الْقَرْنِ الأَوَّلِ.",
 "English Sentence":"§88§ Another century followed during which people venerated and respected those statues more than they did during the first century. §89§ Then a third century followed, and the people said, \"Our forefathers venerated these statues for no other reason than the desire to enjoy their intercession before God.\""
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§40§ ثُمَّ جَاءَ مِنْ بَعْدِهِمُ الْقَرْنُ الثَّالِثُ فَقَالُوا\" مَا عَظَّمَ أَوَّلُونَا هَؤُلاءِ, إِلا وَهُمْ يَرْجُونَ شَفَاعَتَهُمْ عِنْدَ اللَّهِ.",
 "English Sentence":"§89§ Then a third century followed, and the people said, \"Our forefathers venerated these statues for no other reason than the desire to enjoy their intercession before God.\" §90§ Consequently they worshipped them, and became far game in disbelief."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§41§ فَعَبَدُوهُمْ, وَعَظُمَ أَمْرُهُمْ وَاشْتَدَّ كُفْرُهُمْ.",
 "English Sentence":"§90§ Consequently they worshipped them, and became far gone in disbelief."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§42§ فَبَعَثَ اللَّهُ إِلَيْهِم إِدْرِيس عَلَيْهِ السَّلَام (وَهُوَ أحنوخ بن يارد بن مهلاييل بن قينان) نَبِيًّا فَدَعَاهُمْ فَكَذَّبُوهُ فَرَفَعَهُ اللَّهُ إِلَيْهِ مَكَانًا عليا.",
 "English Sentence":"§91§ Thereupon God sent unto them the Prophet Idris, who is Enoch (Akhnukh) the son of Jared the son of Mahaleel the son of Cainan. §92§ Idris called upon the people to repent and warned them, but they believed him not and hearkened not unto his voice. §93§ Therefore God \"uplifted him to a place on high."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§43§ قالت الحكماء\" مما يجب للصديق على الصديق، الإغضاء عن زلاته، والتجاوز عن سيآته، فإن رجع وأعتب وإلا عاتبته بلا إكثار؛ فإن كثرة العتاب مدرجة للقطيعة.",
 "English Sentence":"§94§ Wise men have said, \"Among the things a person owes his friend is to overlook his lapses and disregard his misdeeds. §95§ If he corrects himself and satisfies you, \"well and good;\" otherwise, reprove him gently, for excessive reproof leads to alienation."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§44§ وكذا الذّوات الرّوحانيّة والقوّة الجامعة للكلّ من غير تفصيل هي القوّة الإلهيّة الّتي انبثّت في جميع الموجودات كلّيّة وجزئيّة وجمعتها وأحاطت بها من كلّ وجه، لا من جهة الظّهور ولا من جهة الخفاء ولا من جهة الصّورة ولا من جهة المادّة فالكلّ واحد وهو نفس الذّات الإلهيّة وهي في الحقيقة واحدة بسيطة والاعتبار هو المفصّل لها كالإنسانيّة مع الحيوانيّة.",
 "English Sentence":"§96§ The same applies to the spiritual essences. Now, the power combining everything without any particularization is the divine power. §97§ It is the power distributed over all existing things, whether they are universals or particulars, combining and comprising them in every aspect, with regard to appearance and hiddenness and with regard to form and matter. §98§ Everything is one. §99§ (Oneness) is identical with the divine essence. §100§ In reality, (the divine essence) is one and simple. §101§ The thing that divides it is the way (we) look at it."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§45§ ألا ترى أنّها مندرجة فيها وكائنة بكونها.",
 "English Sentence":"§98§ Everything is one. §99§ (Oneness) is identical with the divine essence. §100§ In reality, (the divine essence) is one and simple. §101§ The thing that divides it is the way (we) look at it."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§46§ فتارة يمثّلونها بالجنس مع النّوع، في كلّ موجود كما ذكرناه وتارة بالكلّ مع الجزء على طريقة المثال.",
 "English Sentence":"§103§ At times, (the Sufis) represent the relationship as that of genus to species, (which exists) in every existing thing, as we have mentioned. §104§ Or, they represent it as that of the universal to the particular, according to the theory of ideas (mithal.)"
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§47§ والّذي يظهر من كلام ابن دهقان في تقرير هذا المذهب أنّ حقيقة ما يقولونه في الوحدة شبيه بما تقوله الحكماء في الألوان من أنّ وجودها مشروط بالضّوء فإذا عدم الضّوء لم تكن الألوان موجودة بوجه.",
 "English Sentence":"§105§ It appears from the discussion of Ibn Dihaq, who explains this (Sufi) theory, that what the (Sufis) say about oneness is actually similar to what the philosophers say about colors, namely, that their existence is predicated upon light. §106§ When there is no light, no colors whatever exist."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§48§ وكذا عندهم الموجودات المحسوسة كلّها مشروطة بوجود المدرك الحسيّ، بل والموجودات المعقولة والمتوهّمة أيضا مشروطة بوجود المدرك العقليّ فإذا الوجود المفصّل كلّه مشروط بوجود المدرك البشريّ.",
 "English Sentence":"§107§ Thus, the (Sufis) think that all existing sensibilia are predicated upon the existence of some (faculty of) sensual perception and, in fact, that all existing intelligibilia and objects of imagination are predicated upon the existence of some (faculty of) intellectual perception. §108§ Thus, every particular in existence is predicated upon (the existence of) the human (faculty) that perceives it."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§49§ فلو فرضنا عدم المدرك البشريّ جملة لم يكن هناك تفصيل الوجود بل هو بسيط واحد فالحرّ والبرد والصّلابة واللّين بل والأرض والماء والنّار والسّماء والكواكب، إنّما وجدت لوجود الحواسّ المدركة لها لما جعل في المدرك من التّفصيل الّذي ليس في الموجود وإنّما هو في المدارك فقط فإذا فقدت المدارك المفصّلة فلا تفصيل إنّما هو إدراك واحد وهو أنا لا غيره.",
 "English Sentence":"§109§ If we assumed that no human being with perception exists, there would be no particularization in existence. §110§ Existence would be simple and one. §111§ Thus, heat and cold, solidity and softness, and, indeed, earth, water, fire, heaven, and the stars, exist only because the senses perceiving them exist, because particularization that does not exist in existence is made possible for the (person) who perceives. §112§ It exists only in perception. §113§ If there were no perceptions to create distinctions, there would be no particularization, but just one single perception, namely, the \"I\" and nothing else."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§50§ ويعتبرون ذلك بحال النّائم فإنّه إذا نام وفقد الحسّ الظّاهر فقد كلّ محسوس وهو في تلك الحالة إلّا ما يفصّله له الخيال.",
 "English Sentence":"§114§ They consider this comparable to the condition of a sleeper. §115§ When he sleeps and has no external sense perception, he loses in that condition all (perception of) sensibilia, with the exception of the things that the imagination particularizes for him."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§51§ قالوا\" فكذا اليقظان إنّما يعتبر تلك المدركات كلّها على التّفصيل بنوع مدركة البشريّ ولو قدّر فقد مدركة فقد التّفصيل وهذا هو معنى قولهم الموهم لا الوهم الّذي هو من جملة المدارك البشريّة.",
 "English Sentence":"§116§ They continued by saying that a person who is awake likewise experiences particularized perceptions only through the type of human perception (that exists) in him. §117§ If he had not that something in him that perceives, there would be no particularization. §118§ This is what the (Sufis) mean when they say \"imaginary.\" §119§ They do not mean \"imaginary\" as a part (in the sequence) of human perceptions."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§52§ هذا ملخّص رأيهم على ما يفهم من كلام ابن دهقان وهو في غاية السّقوط لأنّا نقطع بوجود البلد الّذي نحن مسافرون عنه وإليه يقينا مع غيبته عن أعيننا وبوجود السّماء المظلّة والكواكب وسائر الأشياء الغائبة عنّا.",
 "English Sentence":"§120§ This is a short exposition of (Sufi) opinion, as gathered from the discussion of Ibn Dihaq. §121§ It is most erroneous. We know for certain that a country which we have quitted on our travels or to which we are traveling, exists, despite the fact that we do not see it any more. §122§ We also have definite knowledge of the existence of heaven that overlooks (everything), and of the stars, and of all the other things that are remote from us."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§53§ والإنسان قاطع بذلك ولا يكابر أحد نفسه في اليقين مع أنّ المحقّقين من المتصوّفة المتأخّرين يقولون إنّ المريد عند الكشف ربّما يعرض له توهّم هذه الوحدة ويسمّى ذلك عندهم مقام الجمع ثمّ يترقّى عنه إلى التّمييز بين الموجودات ويعبّرون عن ذلك بمقام الفرق وهو مقام العارف المحقّق.",
 "English Sentence":"§123§ Man knows these things for certain. §124§ No one would deny to himself (the existence of) certain knowledge. §125§ In addition, competent recent Sufis say that during the removal (of the veil), the Sufi novice often has a feeling of the oneness (of existence). §126§ Sufis call that the station of \"combination\" (jam'). §127§ But then, he progresses to distinguishing between existent things. §128§ That is considered by the Sufis the station of \"differentiation\" (farq). §129§ That is the station of the competent gnostic."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§54§ ثمّ إنّ هؤلاء المتأخّرين من المتصوّفة المتكلّمين في الكشف وفيما وراء الحسّ توغّلوا في ذلك فذهب الكثير منهم إلى الحلول والوحدة كما أشرنا إليه وملئوا الصّحف منه مثل الهرويّ في كتاب المقامات له وغيره.",
 "English Sentence":"§130§ The recent Sufis who speak of the removal (of the veil) and supersensory perception have delved deeply into these (subjects). §131§ Many of them turned to (the theory of) incarnation and oneness, as we have indicated. §132§ They have filled many pages with (their exposition of) it. §133§ That was done, for instance, by al-Harawi, in the Kitab al-Maqamat, and by others."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§55§ وتبعهم ابن العربيّ وابن سبعين وتلميذهما ابن العفيف وابن الفارض والنّجم الإسرائيليّ في قصائدهم.",
 "English Sentence":"§134§ They were followed by Ibn al-'Arabi and Ibn Sab'in and their pupils, and then by Ibn al-'Afif ('Afif-ad-din), Ibn al-Farid, and Najm-ad-din al-Isra'ili, in the poems they composed."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§56§ وكان سلفهم مخالطين للإسماعيليّة المتأخّرين من الرّافضة الدّائنين أيضا بالحلول وإلهيّة الأئمّة مذهبا لم يعرف لأوّلهم فأشرب كلّ واحد من الفريقين مذهب الآخر.",
 "English Sentence":"§135§ The early (Sufis) had had contact with the Neo-Ismailiyah Shi'ah extremists who also believed in incarnation and the divinity of the imams, a theory not known to the early (Isma'iliyah). §136§ Each group came to be imbued with the dogmas of the other."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§57§ وقد أشار إلى ذلك ابن سينا في كتاب الإشارات في فضول التّصوّف منها فقال\" «جلّ جناب الحقّ أن يكون شرعة لكلّ وارد أو يطّلع عليه إلّا الواحد بعد الواحد.",
 "English Sentence":"§137§ Avicenna referred to this in the sections on Sufism in the Kitab al-Isharat. §138§ He said\" \"The majestic Truth is too exalted to be available equally to all who seek it, or to be seen save by one person at a time."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§58§ وهذا كلام لا تقوم عليه حجّة عقليّة ولا دليل شرعيّ وإنّما هو من أنواع الخطابة وهو بعينه ما تقوله الرّافضة ودانوا به.",
 "English Sentence":"§139§ The theory of (successive \"poles\") is not confirmed by logical arguments or evidence from the religious law. §140§ It is a sort of rhetorical figure of speech. §141§ It is identical with the theory of the extremist Shi'ah about the succession of the imams through inheritance."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§59§ ثمّ قالوا بترتيب وجود الإبدال بعد هذا القطب كما قاله الشّيعة في النّقباء.",
 "English Sentence":"§142§ Clearly, mysticism has plagiarized this idea from the extremist Shi'ah and come to believe in it. §143§ The (Sufis), furthermore, speak about the order of existence of the \"saints\" who come after the \"pole,\" exactly as the Shi'ah speak about their \"chiefs."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§60§ وإلّا فعليّ رضي الله عنه لم يختصّ من بين الصّحابة بتخلية ولا طريقة في لباس ولا حال.",
 "English Sentence":"§144§ Among the men around Muhammad, 'Ali was not distinguished by any particular practice or way of dressing or by any special condition."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§61§ بل كان أبو بكر وعمر رضي الله عنهما أزهد النّاس بعد رسول الله صلّى الله عليه وسلّم وأكثرهم عبادة.",
 "English Sentence":"§145§ Abu Bakr and 'Umar were the most ascetic and pious people after the Messenger of God."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§62§ ولم يختصّ أحد منهم في الدّين بشيء يؤثر عنه في الخصوص بل كان الصّحابة كلّهم أسوة في الدّين والزّهد والمجاهدة.",
 "English Sentence":"§146§ Yet, none of these men was distinguished by the possession of any particular religious practice exclusively peculiar to him. §147§ In fact, all the men around Muhammad were models of religion, austerity, asceticism, and (pious) exertion."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§63§ والّذي يظهر أنّ المتصوّفة بالعراق، لمّا ظهرت الإسماعيليّة من الشيعة، وظهر كلامهم في الإمامة وما يرجع إليها ما هو معروف، فاقتبسوا من ذلك الموازنة بين الظاهر والباطن وجعلوا الإمامة لسياسة الخلف في الانقياد إلى الشرع، وأفردوه بذلك أن لا يقع اختلاف كما تقرّر في الشّرع.",
 "English Sentence":"§148§ It is obvious that the Sufis in the 'Iraq derived their comparison between the manifest and the inner (world) from the Isma'iliyah Shi'ah and their well-known theory concerning the imamate and connected matters, at the time when the Isma'iliyah Shi'ah made its appearance. §149§ The (Isma'iliyah Shi'ah) considered the leadership of mankind and its guidance toward the religious law a duty of the imam. §150§ Therefore, they assumed that there could be no more than one imam if the possibility of a split were to be avoided, as is established in the religious law."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§64§ ثمّ جعلوا القطب لتعليم المعرفة باللَّه لأنّه رأس العارفين، وأفردوه بذلك تشبيها بالإمام في الظاهر وأن يكون على وزانه في الباطن وسمّوه قطبا لمدار المعرفة عليه، وجعلوا الأبدال كالنقباء مبالغة في التشبيه فتأمّل ذلك.",
 "English Sentence":"§151§ (Correspondingly, the Sufis) then regarded as a duty of the \"pole,\" who is the chief gnostic, the instruction (of mankind) in the gnosis of God. §152§ Therefore, they assumed that there could be only one, on analogy from the imam in the manifest (world), and that he was the counterpart of the imam. §153§ They called him \"pole,\" because the gnosis revolves around him, and they equated the \"saints\" with the 'Alid \"chiefs,\" in their exaggerated desire to identify (their concepts with those of the Shi'ah."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§65§ يشهد لذلك من كلام هؤلاء المتصوفة في أمر الفاطميّ وما شحنوا كتبهم في ذلك ممّا ليس لسلف المتصوفة فيه كلام بنفي أو إثبات وإنّما هو مأخوذ من كلام الشّيعة والرّافضة ومذاهبهم في كتبهم.",
 "English Sentence":"§154§ An instance of what I have just been saying is the lengthy discussion of the Fatimid in Sufi works. §155§ The early Sufis made neither negative nor affirmative statements on the Fatimid. §156§ The lengthy discussion of (recent) Sufis was derived from the discussion (of the subject) and the dogmas (concerning it) expressed by the extremist Shi'ah in their works."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§66§ ولا حرج على من وحّد الحقّ مع بقاء الرسوم والآثار، وإنّما هو من باب\" «حسنات الأبرار سيّئات المقرّبين».",
 "English Sentence":"§157§ There is no objection to a person's declaring the oneness of the Truth, while retaining the outlines and traces (of worldliness). §158§ This belongs to the chapter (dealing with the fact) that the good actions of pious people may be the bad actions of persons who are close to the Divine."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§67§ لأنّ ذلك لازم التقييد والعبوديّة والشفعيّة.",
 "English Sentence":"§159§ It results from the lack of freedom, servitude, and doubleness (of the human condition."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§68§ ومن ترقّى إلى مقام الجمع كان في حقّه نقصا، مع علمه بمرتبته، وأنّه تلبيس تستلزمه العبوديّة ويرمعه الشهود ويطهّر من دنس حدوثه عين الجمع.",
 "English Sentence":"§160§ For those who have ascended to the station of \"combination,\" it constitutes a defect. §161§ They are conscious of their rank and know that (their imperfection) is a deception resulting from (human) servitude, that vision can eliminate it, and that the very essence of \"combination\" can cleanse them from the uncleanliness of their createdness."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§69§ وإذا عرفت المعاني لا مشاحّة في الألفاظ.",
 "English Sentence":"§162§ If the concepts are known, there can be no quarrels about the words."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§70§ والّذي يفيده هذا كله تحقّق أمر فوق هذا الطور، لا نطق فيه ولا خبر عنه.",
 "English Sentence":"§163§ All this teaches realization of the fact that there is something above this level, something about which one cannot speak and about which there is no information. §164§ This much of a hint is sufficient."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§71§ وهذا المقدار من الإشارة كاف.",
 "English Sentence":"§164§ This much of a hint is sufficient."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§72§ والتّعمّق في مثل هذا حجاب، وهو الّذي أوقع في المقالات المعروفة.",
 "English Sentence":"§165§ Going deeply into matters like this (lowers) the veil. §166§ That is the gist of the wellknown (Sufi) statements."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§73§ انتهى كلام الشيخ أبي مهدي الزيّات.",
 "English Sentence":"§167§ Here ends the quotation from shaykh Abu Mahdi b. azZayyat."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§74§ فأمّا الكلام في المجاهدات والمقامات وما يحصل من الأذواق والمواجد في نتائجها ومحاسبة النّفس على التّقصير في أسبابها فأمر لا مدفع فيه لأحد وأذواقهم فيه صحيحة والتّحقّق بها هو عين السّعادة.",
 "English Sentence":"§168§ As for their discussion of pious exertions and stations, of the mystical and ecstatic experiences that result, and of self-scrutiny with regard to (possible) shortcomings in the things that cause these (experiences), this is something that nobody ought to reject. §169§ These mystical experiences of (the Sufis) are sound ones. §170§ Their realization is the very essence of happiness."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§75§ وأمّا الكلام في كرامات القوم وأخبارهم بالمغيّبات وتصرّفهم في الكائنات فأمر صحيح غير منكر.",
 "English Sentence":"§171§ As for their discussion of the acts of divine grace experienced by Sufis, the information they give about supernatural things, and their activity among the created things, these (also) are sound and cannot be. §172§ disapproved of, even though some religious scholars tend to disapprove."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§76§ وإن مال بعض العلماء إلى إنكارها فليس ذلك من الحقّ.",
 "English Sentence":"§172§ disapproved of, even though some religious scholars tend to disapprove. §173§ That is not right."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§77§ وما احتجّ به الأستاذ أبو إسحاق الأسفراينيّ من أئمّة الأشعريّة على إنكارها لالتباسها بالمعجزة فقد فرّق المحقّقون من أهل السّنّة بينهما بالتّحدّي وهو دعوى وقوع المعجزة على وفق ما جاء به.",
 "English Sentence":"§174§ Professor Abu Ishaq alIsfarayini, a leading Ash'arite, argued that these things should be disapproved of, since they might be confused with the (prophetical) miracles. §175§ However, competent orthodox scholars have made a distinction between (miracles and acts of divine grace) by referring to \"the (advance) challenge\" (tahaddi), that is, the claim (made by a prophet in advance) that the miracle would occur in agreement with the prophetic revelation. §176§ It is not possible, they said, that a miracle could happen in agreement with the claim of a liar."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§78§ قالوا\" ثمّ إنّ وقوعها على وفق دعوى الكاذب غير مقدور لأنّ دلالة المعجزة على الصّدق عقليّة فإنّ صفة نفسها التّصديق.",
 "English Sentence":"§177§ Logic requires that a miracle indicate truthfulness. §178§ By definition, a (miracle is something that) can be verified."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§79§ وقد وقع للصّحابة وأكابر السّلف كثير من ذلك وهو معلوم مشهور.",
 "English Sentence":"§179§ Many such acts of divine grace were experienced by the men around Muhammad and the great early Muslims. §180§ This is a well-known and famous (fact)."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§80§ وأمّا الكلام في الكشف وإعطاء حقائق العلويّات وترتيب صدور الكائنات فأكثر كلامهم فيه نوع من المتشابه لما أنّه وجدانيّ عندهم وفاقد الوجدان عندهم بمعزل عن أذواقهم فيه.",
 "English Sentence":"§181§ Most of the (Sufi) discussion of the removal (of the veil), of the reception of the realities of the higher things, and of the order in which the created things issue, falls, in a way, under the category of ambiguous statements. §182§ It is based upon the intuitive experience of (Sufis), and those who lack such intuitive experience cannot have the mystical experience that the (Sufis receive from) it. §183§ No language can express the things that (Sufis) want to say in this connection, because languages have been invented only for (the expression of) commonly accepted concepts, most of which apply to the sensibilia."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§81§ واللّغات لا تعطى له دلالة على مرادهم منه لأنّها لم توضع إلّا للمتعارف وأكثره من المحسوسات.",
 "English Sentence":"§183§ No language can express the things that (Sufis) want to say in this connection, because languages have been invented only for (the expression of) commonly accepted concepts, most of which apply to the sensibilia. §184§ Therefore, we must not bother with the (Sufi) discussion of those matters. We ought merely to leave it alone, just as we leave alone the ambiguous statements (of the Qur'an and the Sunnah)."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§82§ فينبغي أن لا نتعرّض لكلامهم في ذلك ونتركه فيما تركناه من المتشابه ومن رزقه الله هم شيء من هذه الكلمات على الوجه الموافق لظاهر الشّريعة فأكرم بها سعادة.",
 "English Sentence":"§184§ Therefore, we must not bother with the (Sufi) discussion of those matters. We ought merely to leave it alone, just as we leave alone the ambiguous statements (of the Qur'an and the Sunnah). §185§ Those to whom God grants some understanding of those (mystical) utterances in a way that agrees with the plain meaning of the religious law do, indeed, enjoy happiness."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§83§ وأمّا الألفاظ الموهمة الّتي يعبّرون عنها بالشّطحات ويؤاخذهم بها أهل الشّرع فاعلم أنّ الإنصاف في شأن القوم أنّهم أهل غيبة عن الحسّ والواردات تملكهم حتّى ينطقوا عنها بما لا يقصدونه وصاحب الغيبة غير مخاطب والمجبور معذور.",
 "English Sentence":"§186§ (Finally,) there are the suspect expressions which the Sufis call \"ecstatic utterances\" (shatahat) and which provoke the censure of orthodox Muslims. §187§ As to them, it should be known that the attitude that would be fair to the (Sufis) is (to observe) that they are people who are removed from sense perception. §188§ Inspiration grips them. §189§ Eventually, they say things about their inspiration that they do not intend to say. §190§ A person who is removed (from sense perception) cannot be spoken to. §191§ He who is forced (to act) is excused (when he acts, no matter what he does."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§84§ فمن علم منهم فضله واقتداؤه حمل على القصد الجميل من هذا وأمثاله وأنّ العبارة عن المواجد صعبة لفقدان الوضع لها كما وقع لأبي يزيد البسطاميّ وأمثاله.",
 "English Sentence":"§192§ (Sufis) who are known for their excellence and exemplary character are considered to act in good faith in this and similar respects. §193§ It is difficult to express ecstatic experiences, because there are no conventional ways of expressing them. §194§ This was the experience of Abu Yazid al-Bistami and others like him."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§85§ ومن لم يعلم فضله ولا اشتهر فمؤاخذ بما صدر عنه من ذلك إذا لم يتبيّن لنا ما يحملنا على تأويل كلامه.",
 "English Sentence":"§195§ However, (Sufis) whose excellence is not known and famous deserve censure for utterances of this kind, since the (data) that might cause us to interpret their statements (so as to remove any suspicion attached to them) are not clear to us."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§86§ وأمّا من تكلّم بمثلها وهو حاضر في حسّه ولم يملكه الحال فمؤاخذ أيضا.",
 "English Sentence":"§196§ (Furthermore, any Sufis) who are not removed from sense perception and are not in the grip of a state when they make utterances of this kind, also deserve censure."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§87§ ولهذا أفتى الفقهاء وأكابر المتصوّفة بقتل الحلّاج لأنّه تكلّم في حضور وهو مالك لحاله.",
 "English Sentence":"§197§ Therefore, the jurists and the great Sufis decided that al-Hallaj was to be killed, because he spoke (ecstatically) while not removed (from sense perception) but in control of his state. §198§ And God knows better."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§88§ والله أعلم.",
 "English Sentence":"§198§ And God knows better."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§89§ ومن عرض له شيء من ذلك أعرض عنه ولم يحفل به بل يفرّون منه ويرون أنّه من العوائق والمحن وأنّه إدراك من إدراكات النّفس مخلوق حادث وأنّ الموجودات لا تنحصر في مدارك الإنسان.",
 "English Sentence":"§199§ Whenever they had a (supernatural) experience, they turned away from it and paid no attention to it. §200§ Indeed, they tried to avoid it. §201§ They were of the opinion that it was an obstacle and a tribulation and belonged to the (ordinary) perceptions of the soul, and, as such, was something created. §202§ They also thought that human perception could not comprise all the existentia and that the knowledge of God was wider, His creation greater, and His religious law more certain for guidance (than any mystical experience)."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§90§ وعلم الله أوسع وخلقه أكبر وشريعته بالهداية أملك فلا ينطقون بشيء ممّا يدركون.",
 "English Sentence":"§202§ They also thought that human perception could not comprise all the existentia and that the knowledge of God was wider, His creation greater, and His religious law more certain for guidance (than any mystical experience). §203§ Therefore, they did not speak about any of their (supernatural) perceptions."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§91§ بل حظروا الخوض في ذلك ومنعوا من يكشف له الحجاب من أصحابهم من الخوض فيه والوقوف عنده بل يلتزمون طريقتهم كما كانوا في عالم الحسّ قبل الكشف من الاتّباع والاقتداء ويأمرون أصحابهم بالتزامها.",
 "English Sentence":"§204§ In fact, they forbade the discussion of those things and prevented their companions, for whom the veil (of sense perception) was removed, from discussing the matter or from giving it the slightest consideration. §205§ They continued following their models and leading exemplary lives as they had done in the world of sensual perception before the removal (of the veil), and they commanded their companions to do the same."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§92§ هذا العلم من العلوم الشّرعيّة وهو حادث في الملّة عند ما صارت العلوم صنائع وكتب النّاس فيها.",
 "English Sentence":"§206§ This science belongs to the sciences of the religious law. §207§ It originated in Islam when the sciences became crafts and scholars wrote books on them."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§93§ وأمّا الرّؤيا والتّعبير لها فقد كان موجودا في السّلف كما هو في الخلف.",
 "English Sentence":"§208§ Dream visions and dream interpretation existed among the ancients, as among later generations."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§94§ وربّما كان في الملوك والأمم من قبل إلّا أنّه لم يصل إلينا للاكتفاء فيه بكلام المعبّرين من أهل الإسلام.",
 "English Sentence":"§209§ It existed among former (pre-Islamic) religious groups and nations. §210§ However, their dream interpretation did not reach us, because we have been satisfied with the discussions of Muslim dream interpreters."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§95§ وإلّا فالرّؤيا موجودة في صنف البشر على الإطلاق ولا بدّ من تعبيرها.",
 "English Sentence":"§211§ In any case, all human beings can have dream visions, and these visions must be interpreted. §212§ Truthful Joseph already interpreted visions, as is mentioned in the Qur'an."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§96§ فلقد كان يوسف الصّدّيق صلوات الله عليه يعبّر الرّؤيا كما وقع في القرآن.",
 "English Sentence":"§212§ Truthful Joseph already interpreted visions, as is mentioned in the Qur'an."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§97§ وكذلك ثبت عن الصّحيح عن النّبيّ صلّى الله عليه وسلّم وعن أبي بكر رضي الله عنه والرؤيا مدرك من مدارك الغيب.",
 "English Sentence":"§213§ (Sound tradition in) the Sahih, on the authority of the Prophet and on the authority of Abu Bakr, likewise establishes (the existence of dream visions). §214§ Dream vision is a kind of supernatural perception."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§98§ وأمّا السّبب في كون الرّؤيا مدركا للغيب فهو أنّ الرّوح القلبيّ وهو البخار اللّطيف المنبعث من تجويف القلب اللّحميّ ينتشر في الشّريانات ومع الدّم في سائر البدن وبه تكمل أفعال القوى الحيوانيّة وإحساسها.",
 "English Sentence":"§215§ The reason for perception of the supernatural in dream visions is as follows\" The spirit of the heart, which is the fine vapor coming from the cavity in the flesh of the heart, spreads into the veins and, through the blood, to all the rest of the body. §216§ It serves to perfect the actions and sensations of the animal powers."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§99§ فإذا أدركه الملال بكثرة التّصرّف في الإحساس بالحواسّ الخمس وتصريف القوى الظّاهرة وغشي سطح البدن ما يغشاه من برد اللّيل انحبس الرّوح من سائر أقطار البدن إلى مركزه القلبيّ فيستجمّ بذلك لمعاودة فعله فتعطّلت الحواسّ الظاهرة كلّها وذلك هو معنى النّوم كما تقدّم في أوّل الكتاب.",
 "English Sentence":"§217§ The (spirit) may be affected by lassitude, because it is very busy with the sensual perception of the five senses and with the employment of the external powers. §218§ When the surface of the body, then, is covered by the chill of night, the spirit withdraws from all the other regions of the body to its center, the heart. §219§ It rests, in order to be able to resume its activity, and all the external senses are (for the time being) unemployed. §220§ This is the meaning of sleep, as was mentioned before at the beginning of the book."
},
{"Arabic Sentence":"§100§ ثمّ إنّ هذا الرّوح القلبيّ هو مطيّة للرّوح العاقل من الإنسان والرّوح العاقل مدرك لجميع ما في عالم الأمر بذاته إذ حقيقته وذاته عين الإدراك.",
 "English Sentence":"§221§ Now, the spirit of the heart is the vehicle of man's rational spirit. §222§ Through its essence, the rational spirit perceives everything that is in the divine world, since its reality and its essence are identical with perception."
}
]
